<TITLE> OSCE deplores Kyrgyz crackdown on opposition </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 BISHKEK, Dec 25 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Europe's democracy watchdog accused authorities in Kyrgyzstan on Tuesday of the "disproportionate use of force" to stifle opposition protests against the outcome of Sunday's parliamentary election. President Kurmanbek Bakiyev's Ak Zhol party won by far the most seats in the poll held in the volatile Central Asian state. Ata Meken, a radical opposition party, got no seats despite coming second in the vote. The opposition accused the authorities of vote-rigging. Observers from the Organisation for Security and Co-Operation in Europe (OSCE) said the vote had failed to meet its standards. Police cracked down on Ata Meken rallies in the capital Bishkek and some other areas, detaining some protesters. "The Head of the OSCE Centre in Bishkek said he deplored disproportionate use of force by police and the rude and unjustified arrests of NGO and human rights activists that demonstrated against the improper organization of the elections," the OSCE said in a statement issued late on Monday. Kyrgyzstan for many years been seen as an island of relative democracy in largely authoritarian ex-Soviet Central Asia. But the Sunday vote has tarnished the country's reputation. An OSCE official, Markus Mueller, urged Kyrgyz authorities to take steps to improve the situation. "In the interest of the continuation of the democratic process and the stability of the country the shortcomings of the electoral process have to be addressed with a positive and corrective action," the OSCE statement quoted him as sayi
